These define preferred distances between nodes.

---

## Camera/target-like state

There are two small objects:

```js
const currentView = { x: 400, y: 300, phase: 1 };
const targetView  = { x: 400, y: 300, phase: 1 };
```

And each tick it eases `currentView` toward `targetView`:

```js
currentView.x += (targetView.x - currentView.x) * config.phase;
currentView.y += (targetView.y - currentView.y) * config.phase;
currentView.phase += (targetView.phase - currentView.phase) * config.phase;
```

That looks like a camera/focus interpolation, though in this snippet it never changes target values.

---

# Main functions

## 1. Find a node by id

```js
function getNode(id) {
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}
```

---

## 2. Physics update

This is the core simulation.

### A. Pairwise repulsion

For every pair of nodes:

- compute dx, dy
- compute distance
- apply inverse-square repulsive force

Equivalent logic:

```js
for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
  for (let j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
    const dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
    const dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
    const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
    const force = config.repulsion / (dist * dist);

    const fx = (dx / dist) * force;
    const fy = (dy / dist) * force;

    nodes[i].vx += fx;
    nodes[i].vy += fy;
    nodes[j].vx -= fx;
    nodes[j].vy -= fy;
  }
}
```

So all nodes push away from each other.

---

### B. Spring forces on linked nodes

For each link:

- compute displacement from rest length
- apply spring force proportional to stretch/compression

Equivalent:

```js
for (let i = 0; i < links.length; i++) {
  const n1 = getNode(links[i].a);
  const n2 = getNode(links[i].b);
  if (!n1 || !n2) continue;

  const dx = n2.x - n1.x;
  const dy = n2.y - n1.y;
  const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
  const stretch = dist - links[i].rest;
  const force = (links[i].k || config.springForce) * stretch;

  n1.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
  n1.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
  n2.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
  n2.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
}
```

So linked nodes try to stay near their target distances.

---

### C. Damping and center attraction

For each node:

```js
node.vx *= config.damping;
node.vy *= config.damping;

node.vx += (400 - node.x) * config.attractance;
node.vy += (300 - node.y) * config.attractance;

node.x += node.vx;
node.y += node.vy;
```

This keeps the graph from drifting away forever and smooths motion.

---

## 3. Particle spawning

Every 3 ticks, it creates a drifting particle from a random node unless the max count is reached.

Equivalent:

```js
function spawnParticle() {
  if (particles.length >= config.maxNodes) return;

  const source = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  const angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  const speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * ROOT_HALF;

  particles.push({
    x: source.x,
    y: source.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + Math.random() * PHI * ROOT_HALF
  });
}
```

`maxAge` is from `0x320 + random * 0x4b0` = `800 + random * 1200`.

These particles are likely decorative.

---

## 4. Particle update

Each particle:

- loses some velocity due to attenuation
- moves
- ages
- gets deleted when too old

Equivalent:

```js
function updateParticles() {
  for (let i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    const p = particles[i];
    p.vx *= (1 - config.attenuation * 0.125);
    p.vy *= (1 - config.attenuation * 0.125);
    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;
    p.age++;

    if (p.age > p.maxAge) {
      particles.splice(i, 1);
    }
  }
}
```

---

## 5. View smoothing

```js
function updateView() {
  currentView.x += (targetView.x - currentView.x) * config.phase;
  currentView.y += (targetView.y - currentView.y) * config.phase;
  currentView.phase += (targetView.phase - currentView.phase) * config.phase;
}
```

Again, probably meant for rendering/camera interpolation.

---

## 6. Main tick

```js
let tick = 0;

function update() {
  updatePhysics();
  updateParticles();
  updateView();

  if (tick % 3 === 0) {
    spawnParticle();
  }

  tick++;
}

setInterval(update, 16);
```

